<HEADLINE>
<P>
SIKH GROUP BOMBS HINDU PARADE; 32 DIE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BATALA, India 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sikh extremists set off a bomb near a Hindu religious procession in Punjab on 
Tuesday, killing at least 32 people and triggering clashes between the two 
communities, police said. 
</P>
<P>
A police officer died and five were injured as they tried to quell the unrest, 
and 15 more people were killed in violence elsewhere in Punjab. 
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said a procession of 14,000 Hindus, celebrating the birthday of their 
deity Rama, had reached a crowded vegetable market in Batala when the bomb went 
off on a bicycle or scooter. 
</P>
<P>
S. S. Channi, deputy commissioner of Gurdaspur district, imposed an indefinite 
curfew on Batala, an industrial town of 100,000 people in the north of the 
state. 
</P>
<P>
Police said the blast was almost certainly the work of the Khalistan Commando 
Force, Babbar Khalsa and the Khalistan Liberation Force -- a powerful new 
coalition of extremist groups fighting for an independent homeland in Punjab. 
</P>
<P>
They said shrapnel from the bomb killed 10 people in the procession including a 
5-year-old girl watching it with her parents. At least 50 others were taken to 
the hospital with serious injuries. 
</P>
<P>
The girl's mother was among 15 others who died at a Batala hospital shortly 
afterward. Seven more of the injured were sent for care 21 miles to the Sikh 
holy city of Amritsar, where they died. 
</P>
<P>
After the blast, Hindus rampaged through the market trying to set fire to 
vehicles and shops owned by Sikhs. 
</P>
<P>
Police fired in the air to enforce the curfew and to control fighting that had 
broken out between the two groups, senior police Supt. S. K. Goyal said. 
</P>
<P>
Goyal said one police officer was killed and five were injured in the clashes. 
</P>
<P>
Hindus are targets of the extremist campaign in Punjab, in which some 670 
people have died this year alone as Sikhs battle for a homeland they call 
Khalistan -- Land of the Pure. 
</P>
<P>
Sikhs are in a majority in Punjab but make up only 16 million of India's total 
population of 829 million, of which most are Hindus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
