<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEW YORK OVERNIGHT; 
</P>
<P>
EX-GRIDDER MCCONKEY ANNOUNCES HOUSE RACE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TOM POSTER and PHIL ROURA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EX-GIANT McCONKEY WILL RUN FOR CONGRESS: Just as we told you he would, former 
Giants football player Phil McConkey announced Tuesday that he's running for 
Congress as a Republican in New Jersey. He will seek the House seat vacated by 
Rep. Jim Courter, who ran unsuccessfully for governor. 
</P>
<P>
McConkey, who is currently with the San Diego Chargers, told a gathering at the 
Somerville (N.J.) Inn that he will retire from football if elected. 
</P>
<P>
"Some people have criticized me for running for Congress because I wasn't born 
in New Jersey," said the Vietnam veteran. "Well, I bet my grandmother in Italy 
and my grandfather in Ireland never dreamed I might someday be in Congress." 
</P>
<P>
His opponent for the GOP nomination, Rodney P. Frelinghuysen III, traces his 
family to the Mayflower. 
</P>
<P>
Phil, now living in Flemington, N.J., made the announcement with his father, 
Ed, and his girlfriend, model Diane Arabia, at his side. 
</P>
<P>
HUD Secretary Jack Kemp, the ex-Buffalo Bills quarterback, urged him to run. "I 
told him that seats in Congress don't open up that often," Kemp said. 
</P>
<P>
RON'S LETTER MAY FETCH SMALL FORTUNE: Back in '62, the note was just a friendly 
missive from a movie star to a frustrated playwright. But a lot has happened to 
Ronnie Reagan since he starred on TV's "G.E. Theater." And now, the Herman 
Darvick autograph people figure the note may fetch $1,800 at Thursday night's 
auction in the Sheraton City Squire Inn. 
</P>
<P>
The letter was written in April, 1962, to a "Miss White," who'd sent him a 
play. "I must apologize for not getting back to you sooner about your play 
which you kindly forwarded," wrote Reagan. "Frankly, I was motivated by 
selfishness. Since Jan., we've been hanging motionless waiting to see if there 
would be a G.E. Theater next year. Now the ax has fallen. . . . I hope you 
won't mind but now that I know we aren't in the market, I'm taking your play to 
another producer whose show is going &amp; who might be interested." 
</P>
<P>
LITTLE THINGS MEAN A LOT: Hey, Broadway. Think small. At least musically, says 
Martin Charnin, because most of the big houses are occupied with hits. That's 
why Charnin, Jimmy Webb and Peter Stone are writing a "small piece for 10 to 12 
actors" called "Love Me, Love My Dog." Marty will direct, Peter will write the 
book and lyrics, and Jimmy will do the score. 
</P>
<P>
"Peter found an old play by Bill Manhoff, who wrote 'The Owl and the Pussycat,' 
" Charnin said. 
</P>
<P>
"It's a very strange, exotic and bizarre little adventure. It'll be done 
sometime in our immediate lifetimes but all things being equal, that'll be late 
next season." 
</P>
</TEXT>
